So my boyfriend and I were going to a party, but we had some time to kill and we wanted to grab dinner. He has been here before, but this was my first time. First let warn you: depending on the time, the wait can be long, do not drive because there is no paring at all so be prepared to walk. When you walk in you put your name on this chalk board along with number of people in your party. They have seats along the window and along the "bar" for customers to sit on while they are waiting. While waiting you can look at the menus and they have a chalk board that shows their specials and let me be honest, their specials look pretty damn good. I ordered the shrimp and grits while my boyfriend ordered the red beans and rice. We also ordered the crawfish beignets. We were seated pretty quickly and the food came within 5-10 minutes of ordering so we didn't have to wait long the food. The food was so good that if I could grab again right now, I would. The flavors were on point, the shrimp and grits were amazing. Shrimp was cooked perfectly and the appetizer had so many flavors in it that my mouth took awhile to understand what each flavor was. Overall I would definitely come back again and highly recommend it to anyone who either has never had french soul food or just wants some damn good food in the city.

Worth the wait! Bring a book for sure waited 1 hour and 45 minutes on a Sunday. Love the veggie omelette and completely obsessed with the biscuits. Biscuits all day.

I met a friend here for my belated birthday dinner. It has been quite a while (see my review from 2008) since I've been here. My last visit didn't leave a pleasant memory. Yet, my friend chose this spot. I have to admit, I'm so VERY torn between liking the food and not being so crazy about the service. I love that they expanded (that was much needed) and that when I walked in the door, they had a chalk-board for me to register my party. I think that it is a nice touch for the hostess to ask me if I wanted an alcoholic beverage while I waited for my friend (who apparently overshot his muni underground stop...you know who you ARE!). Some areas of improvement: -Service - dunno got a not-so-friendly feeling...like I was just a number and my waitress wasn't too happy to serve us...was kind of rude. -wine in a regular tumbler...like the kind that you see at a cafeteria. I get that it is supposed to be down home, but I just didn't care for it. Probably won't be back, unless forced, and I'm sure that's a-ok to this business as they seem to be rocking along just fine. BTW, out of towners...I would NOT wait in line for this place. Just my opinion.

The food was amazing as always! One of my favorite places in the city to go to but the service was terrible! Every single server had an attitude to begin with and showed a poor reflection of the restaurant. Whether it was getting upset with us for replacing an order that had pork in it (but was not noted on the menu) because of a religious preference to asking about things charged incorrectly on the bill. Not only was our server rude but the server that brought us our food was as well. The other servers didn't even bother looking over at our table when we waved to get their attention.

TIP: Go at night like right after work 5pm...honestly most of the menu is the same and there's little to no wait! Or go with a small group. Or put your name down, go take photos in front of City Hall, browse the farmer's market, AND read in the library to wait the 1.5hr-2hr wait that a group of 4+ usually needs. :P Just BE AWARE! FOOD: Delicious shrimp and grits!!! Sounds super simple but SOOOO out of this world. This is the ONLY place where I enjoy eating grits. I recommend the beignet flight to sample the main fillings. - Plain: It's just okay. When I've gone, it wasn't very flavorful. Just tasted like bread. - Crawfish: It's worth trying! A good amount of filling with a little kick. - Chocolate: There's so many melted (semi-sweet?) chocolate chips! It is overwhelming after a while. - Apple: My favorite. Tastes like an apple pie.

The pulled pork eggs Benedict was cooked perfectly! Nothing to complain about there. Overall, I love the food, service, and atmosphere!! Definitely coming here again and will mos def try the grits!

    5/12/2008Previous review

    It is hard to believe, but my boyfriend pays MORE attention to YELP lists than I DO!!!  In fact, he was the one who had bookmarked this place for us to try for a late Sunday brunch/lunch.  The menu is very simple and down to earth (like all soul food resto menus should be) and it is tucked away in the Tenderloin/Civic Center area.

    Here are my observations:

    -Parking in that area is always a pain in the buttocks (What's new in  the city, right?)
    - Waiting, waiting, waiting....(Of course, I completely forgot that it was Mother's Day...but waiting is the NORM for brunch places that are popular)
    - Limited SPACE.  (Like many cute brunch locales...space is limited so wear DEODERANT AND expect to get cozy with your neighbors, especially if you sit at the BAR).
    - Food is finger lickin' good  (I had the andouille, cheese, scallion omelette with spicy sauce - YUMMMMY)
    - Portion size is more than adequate (I left with a doggy bag)
    - The beignets are GOOD, but NOT GREAT.  (The dough is pretty heavy and will settle like a rock in your tummy)
    - The price is right - moderately priced.  (1 order of beignets, 1 croque monsieur, 1 omelette, 1 cafe au lait = $25/sans tip)
    - The coffee....oh...the coffee...with chickory is OH SO YUMMY

The pulled pork eggs Benedict was cooked perfectly! Nothing to complain about there.

    Overall, I love the food, service, and atmosphere!! Definitely coming here again and will mos def try the grits!
